title: Michael Aular
description: Hi! My name is Michael and for quite some time now there are two things I love to do in my life. The first one is bouldering, the second is coding. Both have changed me drastically and between them there I find a similarity that defines me. Not even that long ago I was, as a Commercial Manager for a production house with several commercial TV productions, responsible for all commercial aspects that are involved in such a production. However, after years of being commercially successful,  I found that I preferred to focus on production instead of sales and was no longer happy with my work. Eventually I decided that it was time for a career change and I went back to school to become a Front-end Web Developer. Here I learned to work with JavaScript, React, HTM5, CSS and SAS. Compared to fellow students, I pick up new languages quickly and feel challenged rather than defeated if something doesn't work right away. It may have taken many hours, had ups and downs and resulted in frustration or, with the desired result, euphoria, but I with hard work I can now finally call myself Front-end Developer. The past few years have been a long climb that I have not regretted a single day! When I started my studies, I started bouldering at the same time; indoor climbing on a wall up to about four meters, without a rope. It is a workout that is very similar to the development I go through as a Web developer. I see every obstacle as a new challenge in which it is often first a puzzle to find the right path, but sometimes it is just a matter of tackling very hard and making progress. I learn from other people with experience, but I am not afraid to find my own path when needed. For both climbing and coding I listen to the advice of experienced people but in the end I have to do it myself. As soon as I master something new there is a feeling of euphoria. Just a little while... because after that I'm already looking forward to the next climb.
tools: React, (S)CSS, JavaScript, HTML5, Redux, Git, and a dash of  common sense

title: Netflix Clone
description: With a couple of colleagues from TechGrounds we were assigned to build a NetflixClone from scratch. For us this meant we started with a study about what we needed to build this site and who would build what kind of components. The entire site is a build in React in which I was responsible for the iconic Netflix lanes. The biggest challenge was to build them in such a way that no matter the length of a given lane (fetched from a library using API calls) the lane would always be endless without any noticeable hiccups when switching from last to first items. Since there aren’t any good components on the web that had this I’ve build everything from scratch making this one of the biggest projects I’ve done so far. I truly enjoyed this build and hope to do more like this in the future.
image1_descr: Fully functioning lanes with minimodals on hover.
image3_descr: Modals filled with moviedata fetched from different API's.

title: Weather App
description: A fullscreen weatherapp I've build for Techgrounds. During this project I've learned to use API calls with a hidden api key in a env file and placed env in gitignore. The API used is from openweathermap.org. There is a possiblity to expand the viewed places (countries, cities, places etc) or close a desired one. Cards can be flipped to get a more detailed prediction. As an extra I've added a background based on the place shown. To achieve this I've used www.openstreetmap.org.
image2_descr: Maps in the background based on  city input
image3_descr: Seven day prediction with matching icons from database

title: Patro Afero Webshop
description: Patro Afereo (meaning dad stuff) is a fictional webshop created for TechGrounds to show my skills with API calls. The first idea was to build a webstore about a uncool product. I've decided to build one around socks and sandals. The two main things were that you'd had to be able to log in and to strore products. For this I've used firebase. All products and images are stored in the database and generated through the use of the website. This means any user could easily add or distract products and both product- and overviewpage would be instantly updated! The site itself is full of lyrics about brown things and the colors are all brown based. The idea was to confuse a little. Is this serious or not? All together Patro Afero shouldn't be taken seriuously though the coding should
image2_descr: A discrete brown shoppingbag to keep in the style of the site
image3_descr: Dropdown menu to select desired products

title: Like Clockwork
description: For this project I decided to combine two different assignments. I've build a analogue clock and placed that more in the background. To challenge myself I've only used JS to build all the elements (although I did styled them in with sass). NExt to this I placed the second a assingment (build a working stopwatch) I made it so that I could switch between a digital clock and the stopwatch. All together it turned out as a nice looking onepager.
image1_descr: Analogue clock based on internal clock
image3_descr: Working clock and stopwatch both build in JS
